               <note>
                  <p>*Note 1: A.G. Day and H. P. &#x0026; E. Day Cos. had a "Pencil Division." Day may have marketed its own pencils though this is less likely than simply producing the parts for others. The elaborate "rope" knurled rings and turnings argue for a date at or before 1880.</p>
               </note>
               <note>
                  <p>*Note 2: <corpname>Waterman-JIF</corpname> was formed in 1926 as an independent though related pen company by <persname>Jules Fagard</persname> who obtains all distrubution rights for <geogname>France</geogname>, <geogname>Belgium</geogname> and their colonies. Fagard became French sub-agent for Sloane in 1915.</p>
               </note>
               <note>
                  <p>*Note 3: Even when not so marked, fountain pen nibs were customarily made (in the U.S.A.) of 14Kt. Gold.  All nibs marked "Waterman" or Caw's" are 14Kt. Exceptions are noted in the listing.</p>
               </note>
               <note>
                  <p>*Note 4: <corpname>ALCO, Aikin-Lambert Co.</corpname>, was a maker of high quality gold pen nibs for dip pens from the mid 19th century.  As Waterman's sales expanded in the 1890s <corpname>Aikin-Lambert</corpname> became a contract supplier of nibs for <corpname>Waterman</corpname> along with it's primary source, <corpname>Leroy Fairchild</corpname>.  Circa 1903 <corpname>Aikin-Lambert</corpname> supplanted <corpname>Fairchild</corpname> as primary source.  At an indeterminate time, most likely between 1905 and 1910, <corpname>Waterman</corpname> acquired <corpname>Aikin-Lambert</corpname>, moving nib making operations in-house.  <corpname>Waterman</corpname> used the name <corpname>Aikin-Lambert</corpname> and the acronym, ALCO, as sub-brands through the 1940s.</p>
               </note>
